Text length: 4153, approximately 8 minutes

Guide reading: from the fever personnel screening classification, to focus on isolation "clear zero" , and then confirmed "clear zero" , the community is undoubtedly the most core of the battlefield, but also under tremendous pressure.

Author | first business | Li Chengwan

"Li's condition has improved and she has been transferred from the critical care hospital to the shelter hospital, but the nucleic acid test has not turned negative and she is still waiting for further treatment, " he said on Feb. 19, ms. Liu, Li's lover, told China Business News.

February 19, for the new crown pneumonia in Wuhan, the last day of the city's large-scale clearance operation. This is a great test for many grass-roots communities and community workers.

From the initial screening of fever personnel in late January, to the early February of the centralized isolation "clear zero" , and then to the new general attack target confirmed "clear zero" , the community is undoubtedly the most central battlefield, but also under tremendous pressure.

On that day, Li Huan, Deputy Secretary of a community in Xinzhou district, Wuhan City, breathed a sigh of relief. Her community had been cleared of "close contacts" and "completed a long and difficult task" during a sweep from Feb. 17 to Feb. 19. But Li Huan they still have to continue to face the shortage of human resources, protective materials, and other practical problems, cheer up and continue to run in each closed community, until the epidemic warning completely eliminated.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Resources that can not be allocated

Li, 56, is a high school math teacher in a district of Wuhan. This year before the Spring Festival, Li continued to have a fever, then went to the hospital for treatment. On January 24, he was diagnosed with suspected new coronary pneumonia, according to a CT diagnostic report, but there was no room for him at the hospital.

At that time, like Li, the number of fever patients in Wuhan continued to explode, and many fever clinics were overcrowded. A reporter visited the Wuhan Red Cross Hospital and found that some patients were sleeping on benches in the hospital lobby because they could not get a bed.

On the day Li took the CT scan, the Wuhan Epidemic Prevention and Control Headquarters issued notice No. 7, saying that in order to solve the problems of long waiting time for fever clinics and delayed bed arrangement, the system of classified medical treatment for fever residents was fully implemented.

At that time, Wuhan required its entire staff to screen fever patients, and the task fell to grassroots communities, "The whole city is responsible for the community, the comprehensive screening of fever patients in the service area (including those who have been treated and those who have not) , and sent to the Community Medical Center for screening and classification of the disease. "

According to the above-mentioned notice No. 7, "for patients who do not need to go to the fever clinic, the implementation of home observation by the community, the community is responsible for doing a good job of home observation services. "

On January 24, the Wuhan Epidemic Prevention and Control Headquarters also issued notice No. 8, "In order to solve the problem of people's home travel inconvenience and other issues, the city has urgently collected 6,000 taxis and allocated them to the central urban area. Each community has 3-5 units, which are uniformly dispatched and used by the neighborhood committees... The neighborhood committees provide home services such as free food delivery, vegetable delivery and medicine delivery to residents with inconvenience to their daily lives."according to public information, there are more than 1,100 communities in Central Wuhan. This means that such a group of community workers with no medical experience in the prevention and control of the epidemic in the first line. But three to five dispatch vehicles, for tens of thousands of people in the community, it is more than enough.

The reporter previously conducted an in-depth survey in several communities and found that in some large communities with tens of thousands of people, there were only about 10 staff members. On the one hand, they had to thoroughly screen patients with fever, and on the other hand, some patients who had been diagnosed were sent to the Medical Center in time, we also need to implement home observation for people with fever.

Do not enter the hospital, Li teacher, that time can only go home "home isolation" treatment. However, home isolation is considered to be a major risk for the spread of the epidemic, as patients become a major source of infection at home, and the care of family members increases the risk of transmission, which also puts great pressure on community prevention and control work. Due to the large number of residents in some communities, home isolation treatment personnel more, community personnel twice a day home temperature, and distribution of living materials, so that they increase the risk of exposure, but also increase the task.

"We don't have enough protective materials, and we need protective clothing, goggles and other equipment to measure our body temperature at home, " a community official in downtown Wuhan told the 1 C reporter. Later, there were new cases of pneumonia in the community, and people were reluctant to open the doors of the buildings, it's also difficult to monitor your temperature at home.

The biggest obstacle is getting to a doctor.

Feng Yichun, an 86-year-old man from the Xichangkou community on the street of Yellow Crane Tower, Wuhan, was diagnosed as a suspected case of new coronary pneumonia on February 8 by a CT scan and has since been confirmed by nucleic acid testing. After two days in isolation at home, he was finally admitted to the hospital.

When Feng Yichun was quarantined at home after his diagnosis, a member of the Xichangkou community told the 1 C reporter that after the family members of the old man brought in the test results, the community had immediately sent an urgent report to the upper level streets of Yellow Crane Tower, "We are in direct contact with these patients, and we are very anxious and do not know the situation of our superiors, but this is the way the procedure goes, and there is nothing we can do. "

According to the 1 C reporter's investigation, the community on the one hand can not implement the hospital bed as soon as possible, on the other hand has no medical ability to carry out the treatment, can only continuously register the information, pacify the patient's family mood, and "gingerly" urges the Superior Street, and so on and so forth.

Yellow Crane Tower Street response 1 C reporter said, confirmed new pneumonia patients, mild to the shelter hospital, severe to the designated Treatment Hospital, "people like Feng Yichun who have been diagnosed with severe illness must be sent to designated hospitals for treatment, and the number of beds will be allocated by the city. "

According to an investigation by 1 C reporters, the power to allocate beds is in the hands of the Wuhan Epidemic Prevention and Control Headquarters. The number of beds for patients to be admitted to hospitals has become "rice in a big pot. " Once there is a vacancy, every district and every street strives for it, want to eat the food from this pot.

"We are very worried, very painful is that the diagnosed and many suspected patients have not been admitted to the designated hospital treatment, can not reach the hospital in time for good treatment, forming a treatment 'Landslide dam' . " At a press conference, Hu Lishan, Wuhan's People's Congress Director and Deputy Party secretary, acknowledged the existence of the "Landslide dam" .

Resistant isolation

Li, who joined the community in 2014, has been serving as deputy secretary, receiving only 2,300 yuan a month, the first time in a long time that the epidemic has caught community workers off guard.

After a failed home quarantine, many families of confirmed and suspected patients eventually need to be placed in isolation. Persuading residents to go to the exclusion zone, however, is no easy task.

Li's community, a sprawling community of more than 2,000 households and tens of thousands of residents, has just 10 staff members, who spend much of their time and energy trying to persuade them to quarantine.

According to Li Huan, a very difficult premise to persuade isolation is that many family members who come into contact with people who have been diagnosed, suspected or had fever always think that their bodies are "ok" and that "they are always worried about the safety of the isolation point. ".

Residents Wang Ping and Sun Lianhua are a couple who live in Li Huan's district. The couple's daughter and son-in-law are suspected of new pneumonia and have been taken to hospital for treatment. After their daughter and son-in-law were taken to hospital, the wangs were left alone at home with their seven-month-old grandson.

"At first, when we screened the returnees, we didn't know how many people there were in the Wang Ping family, " Li said. "They didn't care about the work on the wechat group, and they didn't tell their families where they were going. ".

Only later did the community find out that the wangs were still at home with their grandsons, who were still nursing. Community workers repeatedly called to exhort, but the wangs refused to listen. They also blocked the phone numbers of grid workers and Wechat, and they did not answer calls from community workers.

Li Huan's colleague, Hu Lihua, the Community Secretary, mounted the horse himself. On the morning of February 16, "I spent the whole morning on the phone trying to persuade him, and my voice was hoarse at that time, " Hu told reporters at 1 C.

Still no effect, Hu Lihua can only find help. According to the local measures taken against the quarantined personnel, by the "four guarantees one" personnel that police stations, doctors, community leaders and area grid members, we personally come to exhort.

No one answered the knock at the door. Although the Wangs were at home, they refused to open the door, so they had to force their way in. "They still think they are normal and don't want to go to the quarantine point, and they want to make sure that their grandchild doesn't get new pneumonia. But the community can only cooperate with the work of the higher authorities, so where can they make such promises, " Hu said.

Hu Lihua had to respond to higher authorities. Eventually, the couple and their grandson were sent to isolation. "We asked them to take all the baby's milk powder, diapers and other daily necessities with them. After all, they still need to take good care of the children at this time. "

Community workers have also gone to great lengths to keep Li Yang, a 25 year old resident of the community, from his parents'home. Li Yang, who is suspected of new pneumonia, needs to be quarantined from his parents, according to the local center for Disease Control.

In the afternoon, the community contacted Li Yang's parents, "Our staff tried to talk them out of it, but they refused to go to the quarantine point and both phones were turned off. "The Li believe they are in good health and want to take care of their son, who has just been released from the hospital. I said we can only go to the central quarantine point for observation now, and we will know whether you are normal or not after the quarantine period has passed,"Hu said.

At their insistence, the Li eventually made their way to the quarantine point. On 17 February, community workers told 1 C that Li Yang's mother, Wang, had also been diagnosed with new pneumonia and had been admitted.

"fortunately, there is no danger, or just discharged Li Yang back, Ms. Wang and infected the family, the community will not be at peace. " Speaking of these, Li Huan is still terrified.

A spinning top that won't stop

"after a busy day, even if it's hard work, it's still complained by the residents. " At around 8 p.m. on February 19, Li Huan, who had just finished a three-day sweep of the Internet, still hadn't left work, to 1 C reporter sent two city mayor special line administrative supervision single screenshot. It's about residents complaining about the community, and it's feeding back into the community.

"By order of the city Epidemic Prevention Headquarters, residents can go out every three days to purchase supplies. Today, the community is completely forbidden to go out. Is this an order of the epidemic prevention headquarters, or is the community acting alone? There is no rice for cooking at home, epidemic prevention work should be carried out and residents'livelihood should be protected."The above-mentioned supervision list clearly records the contents of residents'complaints on February 19.

Li Huan and her colleagues feel aggrieved, some whisper: one moment to be fully closed, another can not be completely closed, so that management at a loss. From to now, nearly a month of time, Li Huan and colleagues like a top, in the chain of command in high-speed operation.

Early in the morning of February 11, Wuhan Epidemic Prevention and control again upgraded: The city's residential communities to start closed management, to minimize the flow of personnel. Each family with a pass, every three days can be assigned to go out to purchase living materials.

After a grass-roots visit on Feb. 15, New Wuhan Party Secretary Wang Zhonglin pointed out that there are still some problems in the closed management of some residential areas at this stage. "This problem needs to be well studied so that citizens can buy things without leaving the community, " he said. For example, get a large bag of daily necessities and protective materials, which can be ordered online and delivered directly to their homes or community gates, so that citizens don't have to come out, we can execute the lockdown.

Xinzhou District has also implemented a 100% 24-hour closure of the village, access to the community needs to be strictly registered, and all supermarkets in the area have ceased operation, residents to buy daily necessities through the community staff group purchase.

"after the block was completely closed, residents placed orders on the APP platform provided by the supermarket in the urban area. Today I worked as a porter for a day, carrying vegetables and food for residents, " said Li Huan. But too many people placed orders, the supermarket's APP platform crashed, closed the order, "residents can not buy goods, and angry at us, but also complaints. ".

Cao Xuemei, secretary of the nearby community of Li Huan, is as busy and aggrieved as her colleagues.

Cao lives in a community of 2,000 homes divided into seven subdivisions, all of which are occupied by more than 10,000 residents, most of whom have property management companies. In the midst of managing such a large community, Cao Xuemei and 10 of his colleagues, most of whom are lesbians, are the only people on the job.

Since the case was confirmed before the community, many residents have done a good job of protection, less travel, the community took the initiative to undertake the purchase of living materials residents, the establishment of a number of vegetables, eggs, grain and oil and other materials wechat purchase group. "We asked the suppliers to put them at the gate of the community, and the community staff contacted each family and let everyone line up in turn to get them, " Cao said.

"Some time ago, 10 tons of vegetables came from other places. They stopped at the gate of the community and needed to be unloaded from the truck. It was also our group of Lesbians and a few volunteers who carried the vegetables for several hours before they were finished unloading, " Cao said.

On February 19, Wang Zhonglin, secretary of the Wuhan Municipal Party Committee, said that after the district is closed for management, a strong team of volunteers should be organized to provide services to the elderly who need to buy medicine and can not shop online, to ensure the supply of basic necessities for the residents, and to provide timely feedback on problems that can not be solved.

At present, Li Huan's community has also had many residents volunteer to help. "We live in a community and we are all one family, so it will be fine once we get through this period of time, " community volunteer Mr Du told 1 C.

(community respondents, including Liu Ming, Wang Ping, Sun Lianhua, Li Yang, Li Huan, Hu Lihua and Cao Xuemei, were given pseudonyms.)
